<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  The Web Docs <em>product</em> is built — the FUI generator turns a customer's
  <code>webmanifest</code> + <code>webcases</code> into a served docs site (<code>webdocs/generator.ts</code>,
  backlog #424) — but its <strong>WE-layer spec is greenfield</strong>: <code>webdocs</code> is a
  <code>status: poc</code> stub on the WE side (<code>src/_data/projects/webdocs.json</code>) with no WE
  code surface. This topic surveys how docs generators specify a generation-layout + options
  <strong>contract</strong>, so the WE <strong>Doc Spec</strong> — the contract the generator conforms to
  — can be authored over the shipped impl, constrained by the <a href="/backlog/091-web-docs-as-a-service-plateau/">#091</a>
  docs-as-code ruling (the customer's manifest+cases <em>are</em> the source of truth; Plateau never owns
  content; "cancel and self-host always holds").
</p>

<h2>What the shipped generator already pins (implicitly)</h2>
<p>
  The Doc Spec is a contract authored <em>over a running implementation</em>, not drawn cold. The
  generator already fixes most of the surface:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>The webmanifest</strong> — <code>WebManifest { id, name, description?, blocks? }</code>
    (<code>webdocs/generator.ts:83-89</code>). <code>blocks?</code> is the <em>only</em> layout-bearing
    field: an optional ordered list of block ids the site documents.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>A flat generated model</strong> — <code>DocsSite { pages: DocsPage[] }</code>,
    <code>DocsPage { blockId, cases }</code> (<code>:92-103</code>). The generator emits a <em>data
    model</em>, not rendered HTML — rendering is the renderer's concern.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>The layout rules</strong>, all inside <code>generateDocsSite</code> (<code>:112-118</code>):
    pages follow <code>manifest.blocks</code> order when given, else every case block in stable id order;
    a non-empty <code>manifest.blocks</code> is the <strong>source of truth for scope</strong>; a manifest
    block with no cases still produces an (empty) page.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Zero options</strong> — the signature is the pure <code>(manifest, cases) → DocsSite</code>;
    no presentation/options argument exists.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>The resolver</strong> — <code>bundle | git | registry</code> behind one contract
    (<code>:122-151</code>), already settled by #091 Fork 1's sub-decision; <em>not re-opened</em>.
  </li>
</ul>

<h2>Survey — three archetypes for a generation-layout contract</h2>
<p>
  The six leading docs generators split on a <strong>derived ↔ authored</strong> spectrum:
</p>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Archetype</th><th>Tools</th><th>Where the TOC comes from</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Pure declarative manifest</strong></td>
      <td>Mintlify (<code>docs.json</code> → <code>navigation.tabs[].groups[].pages[]</code>), VitePress
        (<code>themeConfig.sidebar</code>)</td>
      <td>One config lists every page/group; array order = ordering, membership = scope</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Hybrid (autogenerate + overrides)</strong></td>
      <td>Docusaurus (<code>{type:'autogenerated', dirName}</code> + <code>sidebar_position</code>),
        Starlight (<code>autogenerate:{directory}</code> + <code>sidebar.order</code>)</td>
      <td>Config declares the skeleton; <code>autogenerate</code> entries derive sub-trees from the
        filesystem; frontmatter overrides the alphabetic default</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Fully derived from source</strong></td>
      <td>Storybook (the <code>Meta.title</code> <code>"A/B/C"</code> slash-path builds the tree;
        <code>storySort</code> only re-orders), TypeDoc (nav = a projection of the type graph)</td>
      <td>No nav manifest at all — structure is emergent; a config tunes ordering/options only</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p>Findings that shape the forks:</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Hierarchy is universal at the sidebar level</strong> — flat survives only in the top navbar
    (Mintlify <code>tabs</code>, VitePress <code>nav</code> ≤2 levels). The generator's current flat,
    block-keyed page list is the <em>immature</em> shape; the mature end-state is hierarchical. So
    flat-vs-hierarchical is <strong>now-vs-later prioritization, not a merit fork</strong>.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Scope vs presentation: the more derived a system, the more it splits them.</strong>
    Declarative tools <em>fold</em> scope and placement into one ordered array (being listed is both
    inclusion and order); Storybook/TypeDoc cleanly split scope (a glob / entry-set) from a separate sort
    config. The generator today folds (<code>manifest.blocks</code> is both scope and order).
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Mintlify is the single-manifest archetype</strong> — <code>docs.json</code> alone fully
    determines structure, scope, order, and per-node options, reviewable in one diff. The closest prior
    art to a "one manifest → whole site" Doc Spec and the natural fit for #091's single-source-of-truth.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Options stay open in the leaders that scale</strong> — Docusaurus
    <code>sidebar_custom_props</code> + a <code>sidebarItemsGenerator</code> escape hatch, Starlight
    custom <code>attrs</code>. Maps onto the WE house style: standardize the meta-schema, not the list.
  </li>
</ul>

<h2>Placement — settled by statute, not a fork</h2>
<p>
  By the #817 placement test (only types→WE; all runtime→FUI; a runtime symbol stays WE only if a WE-side
  conformance gate consumes it) and the #855 ruling (WE = contracts + conformance vectors; the
  framework-specific generator is impl, never <code>@webeverything</code>), the cut is mechanical:
  <strong>WE owns</strong> the type contracts (<code>WebManifest</code>, <code>WebCases</code>,
  <code>DocsSite</code>) + a golden conformance-vector suite — distributed as the
  <code>@webeverything/contracts/webdocs</code> subpath (#239/#700/#872; the one-line re-export pattern of
  <code>contracts/lifecycle.ts</code>), the vectors riding the <code>conformance-vectors/*.vectors.ts</code>
  kit (#899/#1016). <strong>FUI owns</strong> all runtime (<code>generateDocsSite</code>,
  <code>parseWebCase</code>, <code>resolveWebcasesInput</code>). The genuine forks are about what the
  contract <em>says</em>, not where it lives.
</p>

<h2>Implication for the decision — three forks</h2>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Fork</th><th>Default</th><th>Excluded branch</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>1 · Contract strength</strong></td>
      <td>Deterministic, conformance-locked — WE owns the manifest→DocsSite mapping rules + golden
        vectors; any conforming generator is byte-equivalent on the same input</td>
      <td>Thin type-only contract (mapping is impl freedom) — coherent but breaks #091 no-drift between
        Plateau-hosted and self-hosted output; cf. the #463 module-service determinism precedent</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>2 · Navigation model</strong></td>
      <td>Declarative-manifest authority + derived fallback — the manifest is the authoritative TOC
        (scope+order); blocks omitted ⇒ derive from the cases, alphabetic</td>
      <td>Pure-derived (Storybook model), no manifest authority — contradicts #091 manifest-is-scope-SoT</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>3 · Options locus</strong></td>
      <td>Fold into the manifest as an open declarative <code>docs.*</code> extension; meta-schema
        standardized, not the list</td>
      <td>A separate imperative <code>DocsOptions</code> argument — re-introduces a second source that can
        drift from the manifest, breaking single-source</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p>
  <strong>Supported by default</strong> (no fork): WE/FUI placement (#817/#855); distribution via
  <code>@webeverything/contracts/webdocs</code>; the resolver input shape (#091); flat v1 with a reserved
  forward-compat hierarchy extension point (the #1161 "carry richer fields, not drop them" theme); and
  the webdocs/webmanifests/webcases seam (each spec owns its own envelope — no duplicated schema).
</p>

